{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"111"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/111"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.38,0.08,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108103"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/111"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90513"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108103"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with increasing shortness of breath in the morning. Her chest feels tight, and she is finding it difficult to catch her breath. She suffers from asthma and with her worsening symptoms she has been taking two puffs of her salbutamol inhaler at several times on most days of the week. She has not had any recent respiratory infection and there are no apparent triggers to explain her worsening symptoms. Her inhaler technique is correct. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be added to the current treatment regimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase salbutamol dose to 200 microg inhaled four times daily","Salmeterol 50 microg inhaled twice daily","Fluticasone/salmeterol 250/50 microg inhaled three times daily","Prednisolone 50 mg orally once daily for 5 days","Beclomethasone 100 microg inhaled twice daily"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is exhibiting troublesome symptoms of \u003Cstrong\u003Easthma\u003C/strong\u003E despite significant use of her short-acting bronchodilator (SABA) and correct inhaler technique. In the absence of appreciable triggers that might otherwise be mitigated, she will require a longer-acting agent to provide background relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsthma treatment guidelines recommend starting with a low-dose ICS or low dose budesonide-formoterol for patients with persistent symptoms. This approach targets the underlying inflammation in asthma, reducing the frequency and severity of exacerbations. In this case, if symptoms persist despite the low-dose ICS, the next step would be to switch to regular low dose long-acting beta agonist (LABA) in combination with the ICS, with as-needed SABA, or as SMART.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://files.nationalasthma.org.au/resources/NAC040-Selecting-and-Adjusting-Asthma-Medication-Chart-2024_A4_LR.pdf\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting and adjusting asthma medications for adults and adolescents:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs-needed SABA alone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBudesonide\u2013formoterol (low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS (low dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EREGULAR DAILY ICS\u2013LABA (\u003Cstrong\u003ELOW\u003C/strong\u003E DOSE): ICS\u2013formoterol maintenance-and-reliever therapy (low dose as regular daily maintenance plus low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS\u2013LABA combination (low dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EREGULAR DAILY ICS\u2013LABA (\u003Cstrong\u003EMEDIUM\u2013HIGH\u003C/strong\u003E DOSE): ICS\u2013formoterol maintenance-and-reliever therapy (medium dose as regular daily maintenance plus low dose as needed) OR Regular daily maintenance ICS\u2013LABA combination (medium\u2013high dose) + SABA reliever as needed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdd-on specialised treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) should be added to her regime per standard guidelines, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeclomethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is a typical choice. Inhaled corticosteroids are mostly delivered to the pulmonary tissues, and thereby minimise systemic absorption and the side effects of prolonged steroid dosing. However, poor inhaler technique can adversely affect pulmonary penetration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalmeterol\u003C/strong\u003E is a LABA and should not be used as monotherapy in asthma management. LABAs are effective in providing long-term bronchodilation but do not address the underlying inflammation in asthma. Using a LABA without an ICS can lead to worsening asthma control and increased risk of asthma-related complications. Therefore, it is crucial to pair LABAs with ICS to ensure both bronchodilation and anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluticasone/salmeterol\u003C/strong\u003E is a combination product (ICS/LABA). Regular LABA/ICS is generally only added if a regular ICS OR low-dose budesonide/salmeterol (specifically), plus PRN SABA or the latter as SMART therapy (Single Maintenance And Reliever Therapy) does not provide adequate control. However, SMART is only possible with inhalers containing budesonide because of its rapid onset of action. Salmeterol has a slower onset of action, making it unsuitable for SMART therapy. Furthermore, this option is incorrect as the recommended dosing is twice a day, not three times daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESABA agents are used as \u0027relievers\u0027 due to their quick onset and offset, and are not used for regular dosing. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease salbutamol dose to 200 microg inhaled four times daily \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect. Similarly, oral steroids (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E) are used in acute exacerbations of asthma but are not used for long-term regular dosing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inhaled corticosteroids are a key component in the management of asthma to control inflammation and prevent exacerbations.","Long-acting beta agonists should not be used as monotherapy in asthma management.","Combination inhalers with both an inhaled corticosteroid and a long-acting beta agonist are used when asthma is not controlled with inhaled corticosteroids alone."],"references":["National Asthma Council Australia. Australian Asthma Handbook [Internet]. Australian Asthma Handbook. 2022. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au","Wu TD, Brigham EP, McCormack MC. Asthma in the Primary Care Setting. Med Clin N Am 2019; 103:435-52. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30955512/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90513"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"111"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":